Upon the stage, a solitary light
Illumes the **performer** in her lonely sphere;
Her measured breath dispels the encroaching night,
While silent watchers lean intent to hear.

Her **patterned** gown, a marvel to the sight,
Moves with the grace of seasons turning year;
A practiced step, both fluid and polite,
Conceals the tremor, masks the inner fear.

**Similarly**, we in life's script appear,
Play parts assigned on stages vast and dim;
Our joys and sorrows, every hope held dear,
Are movements learned on impulse or a whim.

